&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;![endif]&gt;Clients generating =
such entry-point URIs via URI
templates and a scripting language&lt;o:p&gt;&lt;/o:p&gt;=
&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D&#39;margin-left:36.0pt&#39;&gt;Conceptually the di=
fference is
that (2) can generate novel URIs that were never returned in an=
y
representation. For example, a geospatial system could have returned mill=
ions
of lat/long URIs in various representations over the years, but never =
returned
one with the specific lat/long that a client script generates, eg =
no one had
ever asked about THAT part of the Pacific yet.&lt;o:p&gt;&lt;/o:p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;=
/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;

&lt;p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D&#39;margin-left:36.0pt&#39;&gt;&lt;o:p&gt;&nbsp;=
&lt;/o:p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;

&lt;p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D&#39;margin-left:36.0pt=
&#39;&gt;But pragmatically there seems to
me to be no difference at all. In other =
words, the idea that&nbsp;one can
substantially reduce the dependencies bet=
ween clients and servers&nbsp;by
returning a network of URIs in representat=
ions (HATEOAS) instead of explicitly
documenting the URI templates that cou=
ld generate them, seems only to work if
one prohibits or at least discourag=
es promiscuous bookmarking of URIs, ie
prohibits deep linking by REST clien=
ts.&lt;o:p&gt;&lt;/o:p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;

&lt;p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D&#39;margin-lef=
t:36.0pt&#39;&gt;&lt;o:p&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/o:p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;

&lt;p class=3DMsoNormal style=
=3D&#39;margin-left:36.0pt&#39;&gt;This is why I think the structure
of URIs IS import=
ant and the use of URI templates is NOT suspect. Do others see
this as a te=
nsion as well, or I am just misunderstanding something?&lt;o:p&gt;&lt;/o:p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;/d=
iv&gt;

